7
[ul 
	[li 
		" Every unique video frame and audio sample that the TASed system generates must be present in the video and audio streams, even if it requires variable framerate.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Video dumping must not affect emulation in any way.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" It must be possible to dump all video frames and audio samples to a file without information loss.
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" There must be a way to dump pixel-perfect video without resizing, the way it's originally generated by the system. Even though some systems only generate composite analog signal, emulators use to generate digital RGB that must be accurately represented in the video dump.
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" Uncompressed encoding is preferred for audio, and lossless is preferred for video.
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" Encoding techniques used for video dumping must provide maximum compatibility to guarantee that it would be easy to further encode the dump.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
		" It must be possible to have a guaranteed way to sustain perfect sync between video and audio for infinite time and infinite number of segments.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" It must be possible to dump in segments:
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" It must be possible to start a new video segment every time resolution or framerate changes.
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" If dumping method is WinAPI/VideoForWindows based, it must be possible to start a new segment before the video file is 2GB in size.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
		" It must be possible to add informational overlay to the dump, for example Lua drawings.
	]li
]ul
